<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE NFL; DEION BECOMES A 49ER, MIGHT PLAY 
AGAINST RAMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 As expected, All-Pro cornerback Deion Sanders ended his free-agent tour by 
rejecting several more lucrative offers in favor of a one-year, $1.1-million 
contract with the San Francisco 49ers. The deal includes $750,000 in 
incentives. 
</P>
<P>
 Sanders took part in workouts with his new team and hopes to play Sunday 
against the Rams. 
</P>
<P>
 In another move, the 49ers signed former Pro Bowl defensive end Charles Mann, 
who was released by the Washington Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 After a half-day walkout before the season began, Sterling Sharpe was ensured 
of being the NFL's highest-paid receiver from the 1995 season through the year 
2000, the Green Bay Press-Gazette reported. 
</P>
<P>
 A new clause stipulates that Sharpe's pay will equal the average yearly salary 
of the league's highest-paid receiver, plus $1. 
</P>
<P>
 Sharpe's deal was also sweetened for this season in which he will earn $2.7 
million -- third highest for a wide receiver -- instead of the $1.3 million 
originally scheduled after the club triggered a $1.4-million escalator clause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
