<P>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL / DAILY REPORT; USC; RECEIVER HERVEY TO MISS NEXT GAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EARL GUSTKEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 USC's pass offense will have to make do without starting wide receiver Ed 
Hervey in the Sept. 24 Baylor game. Coach John Robinson said the knee Hervey 
injured against Washington two games ago will keep him out of a second game. 
</P>
<P>
 Neither Hervey nor Keyshawn Johnson, the other starting wide receiver, played 
against Penn State last week. Johnson was also held out of Thursday's practice 
because of a stubborn thigh injury that has caused knee swelling. 
</P>
<P>
 And quarterback Rob Johnson sat out another practice. He's still nursing a 
sore lower back, picked up in the Washington game. He's expected to participate 
in drills next week, however. 
</P>
<P>
 "I had 11 varsity sports seasons in high school and four years here in 
football, and these are the first practices I've ever missed with an injury," 
Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Quincy Harrison, a sophomore backup cornerback who returned an intercepted 
pass for a 68-yard touchdown at Penn State last weekend, has cracked the 
starting lineup. The Trojans were trailing Penn State, 35-0, early in the third 
quarter when Harrison, from Eldorado High in Las Vegas, intercepted a pass and 
returned it for a touchdown. EARL GUSTKEY 
</P>
