<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIAMOND BAR'S DIMINUTIVE RUNNING BACKS SLICE THROUGH EL DORADO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE TERRY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Terry Roche insists his Diamond Bar football team is young and will have a 
difficult time surviving the Sierra League this fall. But he might have trouble 
convincing El Dorado of that after getting stampeded by the Brahmas, 31-14, 
Thursday at Valencia High. 
</P>
<P>
 The pocket-sized backfield of Scott Williams and Lathian Tyler helped Diamond 
Bar improve to 1-1. Neither is bigger than 5 feet 8, 160 pounds, yet they 
combined for 217 rushing and 65 passing yards. Tyler also scored twice, on runs 
of five and 47 yards. 
</P>
<P>
 Erik Stidham wasn't quite as brilliant at quarterback -- he completed six 
passes for 102 yards and a touchdown and an interception. But the Brahmas' 
defense harassed El Dorado starter Mike Marzicola into three interceptions and 
forced two fumbles. The five turnovers were converted into 17 points. 
</P>
<P>
 "This can be a decent team," Roche said. "We've got young kids but good 
attitudes." 
</P>
<P>
 El Dorado Coach Rick Jones lost more than a season opener. He was nearly 
reduced to asking for volunteers Thursday: seven players, five of them two-way 
starters, watched from the sidelines because of injuries, reducing the 
available roster to 30. During the game, the Golden Hawks lost receiver Kirk 
Badii after a 16-yard catch because of an injured shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
 "The second and third teams did the best they could," said Jones, who already 
called up reinforcements from the junior varsity this week. "And when you're a 
young team learning how to win, sometimes you have to be stomped in the 
process. We're young and we play like it. Right now we need some of our guys to 
step up and take some initiative." 
</P>
<P>
 In the second quarter, Stidham completed a 32-yard touchdown toss to Andrew 
Hackett, who outraced his defender down the right sideline for a 7-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 El Dorado -- which suffered through a miserable half, getting more penalty 
yards (73) than offense (38) -- got an immediate lift from Richie Williams, who 
returned the ensuing kickoff 95 yards for the Golden Hawks' lone score in the 
half. But as soon as the Brahmas got the ball back, they rumbled 63 yards in 
nine plays, Jeremy Ruiz capping the drive with a touchdown from two yards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
