INS CENTER RELEASES 37 MIGRANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thirty-seven Cuban refugees were released from a detention center Thursday 
under a new federal policy that benefits children, their parents and some 
others. 
</P>
<P>
 The group released from the Krome detention center consisted of 19 children 
and 18 adults, said Lemar Wooley, a Miami spokesman for the Immigration and 
Naturalization Service.Most of the adults were mothers of the children, Wooley 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The order cracking down on Cubans arriving in this country by raft was 
loosened Wednesday, Wooley said, to allow the release of children and the 
adults responsible for them, as well as people who would qualify on 
humanitarian grounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials had already released 19 Cubans from Krome in the last month, 
including four pregnant women, a paraplegic man and his wife, and a mother and 
her 2-month-old child. 
