<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; COUNCIL VOTES TO RAISE BUS FARES; 
TRANSPORTATION: PRICES FOR ONE-WAY TICKETS WILL INCREASE TO $2.50 FROM $2 FOR 
ADULTS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DOUGLAS ALGER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Bus riders traveling between the Santa Clarita and San Fernando valleys will 
need more pocket change beginning in October. 
</P>
<P>
 The Santa Clarita City Council voted 5 to 0 Tuesday to raise the cost of 
one-way fares for adults by 25% and to increase other ticket prices to a lesser 
degree. 
</P>
<P>
 Adult fares will go up from $2 to $2.50 for one-way rides, from $40 to $43 for 
20-trip ticket books and from $65 to $70 for monthly passes. Tickets for 
students, senior citizens and disabled riders are half of the adult fare. 
</P>
<P>
 City transit officials established the three express lines -- 796, 797 and 798 
-- after the Northridge earthquake and say the rate increases will make fares 
comparable to other commuter lines now operating from Santa Clarita. 
</P>
<P>
 About 300 riders use the express routes daily between the Santa Clarita and 
San Fernando valleys, according to city Transit Manager Ron Kilcoyne. 
</P>
<P>
 The city pays $1.1 million to provide the service. It now recovers 20% of the 
cost from ticket purchases, and will recover an additional 10% with the fare 
increases, Kilcoyne said. The new ticket prices begin Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
 Some bus passengers complained about the rate increases, saying they will 
discourage people from taking the bus at a time when city officials should be 
encouraging ridership. 
</P>
<P>
 Council members said they prefer to raise rates gradually, and backed off on 
even greater increases that would have priced 20-trip ticket books at $50 and 
monthly passes at $80. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you want to raise your fares $15 a month, you're going to lose riders," 
said Jack Hamilton, a Santa Clarita resident who has ridden the express bus 
service since it began. 
</P>
<P>
 "It seems to me, we're raising it a whole big hunk at one time," said 
Councilwoman Jan Heidt, before voting on the smaller increases. "I know we have 
to adjust it, but can't we make it less painful?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091694-0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 079765 </DOCID>
